# LWC + Stripe Universal Connector Integration

---

## Part 1: Universal Patterns

Applies to any LWC that integrates with Stripe via the Universal Connector. These patterns hold regardless of which Salesforce object or payment flow you're building.

---

### CSP Trusted Sites (CRITICAL — Manual Setup Required)

Stripe Payment Element renders inside secure iframes from `js.stripe.com`. Salesforce's CSP `frame-src` directive blocks third-party iframes by default. Must be configured via **Setup UI** — metadata deployment maps `context=All` incorrectly and does not check all directive boxes.

**Required** (Setup > CSP Trusted Sites):

| Trusted URL | connect-src | font-src | frame-src | img-src | media-src | style-src |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `https://js.stripe.com` | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |
| `https://api.stripe.com` | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ | ✓ |

`frame-src` is the critical one. Without it, `loadScript()` succeeds and the PaymentIntent is created, but the Payment Element iframes render as an empty container with no visible error in the UI — only a CSP violation in the browser console.

---

### Loading Stripe.js

Always load from CDN via `lightning/platformResourceLoader`. Never self-host — Stripe requires CDN loading for PCI compliance.

```javascript
import { loadScript } from 'lightning/platformResourceLoader';
const STRIPE_JS_URL = 'https://js.stripe.com/v3/';

// Guard with a flag — loadScript throws if called twice on the same resource
if (!this.stripeJsLoaded) {
    await loadScript(this, STRIPE_JS_URL);
    this.stripeJsLoaded = true;
}
this.stripe = window.Stripe(publishableKey);
```

Parallelize Stripe.js loading with your Apex call using `Promise.all` — they don't depend on each other:
```javascript
const [config] = await Promise.all([
    createPaymentIntent({ recordId: this.recordId }),
    loadScript(this, STRIPE_JS_URL)
]);
```

---

### Shadow DOM — Data Attributes, Not IDs

LWC Shadow DOM scopes element IDs (e.g. `id="payment-element"` → `id="payment-element-86"`). External scripts like Stripe.js cannot use `document.getElementById()`. Always use data attributes:

```html
<!-- ✅ Correct -->
<div data-stripe-element="payment"></div>

<!-- ❌ Wrong — ID is scoped, Stripe.js can't find it -->
<div id="payment-element"></div>
```

```javascript
const container = this.template.querySelector('[data-stripe-element="payment"]');
this.paymentElement.mount(container);
```

---

### LWC Lifecycle Hooks for Stripe

**`connectedCallback` or user action handler** — load Stripe.js and create PaymentIntent. Never on page load; only on explicit user action to avoid orphan PaymentIntents.

**`renderedCallback`** — the only safe place to mount the Payment Element. The container div doesn't exist until a reactive property (`showPaymentForm = true`) triggers a re-render. Always use a guard flag:

```javascript
renderedCallback() {
    if (this.paymentElement && this.showPaymentForm && !this.paymentElementMounted) {
        const container = this.template.querySelector('[data-stripe-element="payment"]');
        if (container) {
            this.paymentElement.mount(container);
            this.paymentElementMounted = true;
        }
    }
}
```

**`disconnectedCallback`** — always unmount to prevent memory leaks:
```javascript
disconnectedCallback() {
    if (this.paymentElement) {
        try { this.paymentElement.unmount(); } catch(e) {}
    }
}
```

---

### Security & PCI Compliance

- **Publishable key** — safe to send to the client; identifies your Stripe account, not a secret
- **Secret key** — never touched by LWC; handled entirely by the Universal Connector via encrypted `Access_Token__c`
- **`clientSecret`** — transient, single-use, never persisted in Salesforce; return it from Apex and use it for the session only
- **Card data** — never touches Salesforce; Stripe Payment Element uses secure iframes that POST directly to Stripe's servers

---

### Payment Confirmation

Use `redirect: 'if_required'` to handle 3D Secure / SCA without forcing a page redirect:

```javascript
const { error, paymentIntent } = await this.stripe.confirmPayment({
    elements: this.elements,
    confirmParams: { return_url: window.location.href },
    redirect: 'if_required'
});
```

After confirmation, `paymentIntent` contains:
- `paymentIntent.id` — the `pi_xxx` PaymentIntent ID
- `paymentIntent.latest_charge` — the `ch_xxx` Charge ID (available after `succeeded`)
- `paymentIntent.status` — `succeeded`, `requires_action`, or another terminal state

Always handle all three status branches: `succeeded`, `requires_action` (3DS), and fallback error.

Client-side `paymentIntent.status === 'succeeded'` is **not** enough to mark the Salesforce record as paid. Treat the browser result as a UX signal only. Before setting any "captured", "paid", or reconciliation fields in Salesforce, make a server-side verification call to Stripe using the Universal Connector and confirm:

- the PaymentIntent still has `status = succeeded`
- the PaymentIntent metadata maps back to the expected Salesforce record
- the amount and currency still match the Salesforce-side expectation
- the charge or payment intent has not already been linked to a different Salesforce record

---

### Post-Payment: Writing Back to Salesforce

Call a separate `@AuraEnabled` Apex method after confirmation — never block the success UI waiting for DML. Use fire-and-forget:

```javascript
recordPaymentSuccess({
    recordId: this.recordId,
    paymentIntentId: paymentIntent.id,
    chargeId: paymentIntent.latest_charge || ''
}).then(() => {
    getRecordNotifyChange([{ recordId: this.recordId }]);
}).catch(err => console.error(err));
```

Use `getRecordNotifyChange` (not `refreshApex`) to push the wire refresh to all components watching the record after the DML update.

If you write back to Salesforce after payment, prefer one of these patterns:

1. **Best**: fetch the PaymentIntent server-side and verify status, metadata, amount, and currency before updating any record fields
2. **Acceptable for demos only**: clearly document that the component trusts the client-confirmed result and is not a production-grade payment reconciliation path

Never blindly trust `paymentIntent.id` or `latest_charge` values supplied by the browser when updating business-critical fields.

**Idempotency state**: Wire a "payment captured" boolean field from the record. Gate your initial UI state on it so the Pay Now button never re-appears on a previously paid record — this works retroactively for all existing records with the field already set:

```javascript
get showPayButton() {
    return !this.paymentCaptured && !this.paymentSuccess && !this.showPaymentForm;
}
get showCapturedState() {
    return this.paymentCaptured && !this.paymentSuccess; // in-session success takes priority
}
```

---

### Charge Record Timing (Webhook Lag)

When `confirmPayment` succeeds on the client, `stripeGC__Charge__c` almost certainly does not exist in SF yet — the `charge.succeeded` webhook is async and takes seconds to arrive and be processed. Never query for it synchronously in the post-payment Apex method.

Pattern: try the sync lookup first (fast path for cases where webhook was already processed), then fall back to a Queueable with delay:

```apex
List<stripeGC__Charge__c> charges = [
    SELECT Id FROM stripeGC__Charge__c
    WHERE stripeGC__Stripe_Id__c = :chargeId
    WITH USER_MODE LIMIT 1
];
if (!charges.isEmpty()) {
    charges[0].Opportunity__c = recordId;
    update charges[0];
} else {
    System.enqueueJob(new ChargeLinkerQueueable(recordId, chargeId, 0), 1);
}
```

Queueable should retry up to 3 times with 1-minute delay (`System.enqueueJob(job, delayInMinutes)` — available API 57+). The delay is a backend-only operation with zero UX impact.

When linking the resulting `stripeGC__Charge__c` or updating the parent Salesforce record, prefer user-mode DML or explicit CRUD/FLS enforcement if the component is intended as a reusable production reference. `with sharing` plus `WITH USER_MODE` SOQL does not automatically protect field writes.

---

### Stripe Customer Lookup

**The relationship is Customer → Account, not Account → Customer.** `stripeGC__Customer__c` holds the lookup to Account via `stripeGC__Account__c`. The Account page layout does not surface the Stripe Customer ID.

Always query the Customer by AccountId to get the `cus_xxx` ID for PaymentIntent creation:

```apex
List<stripeGC__Customer__c> customers = [
    SELECT stripeGC__Stripe_Id__c
    FROM stripeGC__Customer__c
    WHERE stripeGC__Account__c = :accountId
    WITH USER_MODE
    LIMIT 1
];
if (!customers.isEmpty() && String.isNotBlank(customers[0].stripeGC__Stripe_Id__c)) {
    params.customer = customers[0].stripeGC__Stripe_Id__c;
}
```

If no Customer exists for the Account yet (e.g. Customer creation flow hasn't run), omit `params.customer` — the PaymentIntent is created as a guest. This is expected and handled gracefully by leaving the field null.

---

### PaymentIntent Metadata

Use `v02_Metadata` and `v02_AdditionalString` to attach key-value pairs to a PaymentIntent. The property name is `listAdditionalStringField` — not obvious from the class name:

```apex
stripeGC.v02_Metadata metadata = new stripeGC.v02_Metadata();
metadata.listAdditionalStringField = new List<stripeGC.v02_AdditionalString>{
    new stripeGC.v02_AdditionalString('salesforce_record_id', recordId),
    new stripeGC.v02_AdditionalString('salesforce_record_name', recordName)
};
params.metadata = metadata;
```

Metadata lives on the Stripe PaymentIntent only — visible in the Stripe Dashboard, useful for reconciliation. It does **not** automatically populate any SF field (including `Charge.Opportunity__c`). Any SF field population requires explicit Apex or a Flow.

---

### Universal Connector Apex Conventions

- Always pass `accountRecordId` (Stripe Account SF record ID, not the Stripe account string)
- Always set `performDmlSaveAfterCalls = true` for standalone Apex calls; `false` only when chaining multiple callouts
- Always set `ignoreBillingSyncEventProcessing = true` to prevent event processing loops
- Amount is always in smallest currency unit (dollars × 100 = cents)
- `WITH USER_MODE` on all SOQL queries
- Wrap the Stripe Account lookup in a connected check: `WHERE stripeGC__Is_Connected__c = true`

---

### Common Mistakes

1. **Using element IDs for Stripe mount target** — Shadow DOM scopes them; use `data-*` attributes
2. **Mounting Payment Element in connectedCallback** — DOM container doesn't exist yet; use `renderedCallback` with guard flag
3. **Self-hosting Stripe.js** — Violates Stripe TOS; always load from `js.stripe.com` CDN
4. **Deploying CSP Trusted Sites via metadata** — `context=All` doesn't check all boxes; configure via Setup UI
5. **Relying on frame-src being set automatically** — It's the critical checkbox; without it, Payment Element renders empty with no obvious error
6. **Creating PaymentIntent on page load** — Creates orphan intents; only create on explicit user action
7. **Persisting clientSecret** — Never store it; it's single-use and session-scoped
8. **Forgetting amount conversion** — Salesforce currency fields are dollars; Stripe expects cents (× 100)
9. **Querying `stripeGC__Charge__c` synchronously after confirmPayment** — Webhook lag means the record won't exist yet; use Queueable with delay
10. **Looking up Stripe Customer ID from Account** — The lookup is on `stripeGC__Customer__c.stripeGC__Account__c`, not on Account; query Customer by AccountId
11. **Using `refreshApex` after DML** — Use `getRecordNotifyChange([{ recordId }])` to notify all wire adapters watching the record
12. **Showing action buttons without checking payment state** — Always wire a captured/processed boolean field from the record and gate all action states on it
13. **Marking Salesforce records as paid from browser state alone** — always re-verify the PaymentIntent server-side before updating business-critical fields
14. **Assuming `with sharing` covers field writes** — it does not enforce CRUD/FLS on DML; use user-mode DML or explicit checks for reusable production assets

